@DATABASE Palettes.guide

@NODE MAIN "Palettes"

@{" Info Palette    " link INFO}  General editor information palette.
@{" Surface Palette " link SURF}  Surface selection/description palette.
@ENDNODE

@NODE INFO "Palettes: Info Palette"

  The Info Palette allows you to see general information on the editors
current status.

  The area in the center of the palette is a proportional gadget that allows
you to quickly move to a different area of the track or to get an idea of
your current location.  Clicking & Dragging the white box with the left mouse
button will allow you to move it to another area of the track, within the
boxed zone.

  The box to the right of the palette will display the currently selected
tile if any have been loaded.

  Other text on this palette is as follows:

    @{B}Tile:@{UB}    This is the currently selected tile number & bank.
             The first number is the tile, the second after the '/'
             is the bank for the current tile type.

    @{B}Object:@{UB}  This shows which object proto-type number or cash value
             is currently selected

    @{B}Surface:@{UB} This shows the currently selected @{" Surface Track Code " link SURF}.

    @{B}Mode:@{UB}    This shows which editing mode the editor is currently in.

    @{B}Pos:@{UB}     This shows the track cell the mouse is currently located in.
             The number refers to 64 by 64 pixel squares on the track area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SURF "Palettes: Surface Palette"

  The Surface Palette allows you to select or view available surfaces.  You
can select the surface type you wish to use by clicking on the entry with the
left mouse button.  You can scroll the list up and down with the slider bar
on the right hand side or enlarge/reduce the size of the palette using the
size gadget.

  The Surface Palette shows you a list of available surface types in the
following format:


    @{B}<Surface Number> <Surface Track Code> <Surface Name/Description>@{UB}


    @{B}Surface Number:@{UB}     The number of the surface in increasing order.

    @{B}Surface Track Code:@{UB} The value you will see if you have 'Show Surfaces'
                        enabled, on the track display. You can use this
                        value to find out what a particular surface of a
                        track is.

    @{B}Surface Name:@{UB}       The name/description of what a particular surface
                        is.

  You can also select a surface by typing it's surface number on the numeric
keypad.  You must type a two digit number, if you think you have made a
mistake, pressing the 'Enter' key will ignore the number you started to type
and wait for a full two digits.

  For more information on surfaces see @{" Surfaces " link "Describe.Menu/Surfaces"}.

@ENDNODE
